<p align="center"><strong><font size="+1">U.S. Team Joininng Fight to Stem Rare Fatal Fever in Africa</font></strong> 
<p align="center">By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
<p>The United States Public Health Service, responding to a request from the Government of Sierra Leone, is sending a team of six experts to fight a new outbreak of Lassa fever, a mysterious, lethal viral disease.</p>
<p>Full details are not available about the outbreak of Lassa fever infections, against which there are no known effective drug therapies.</p>
<p>Federal health officials said yesterday that on the basis of current information at least 46 cases of Lassa fever had been diagnosed in recent months in <strong>Panguma</strong>, which is in eastern Sierra Leone.</p>
<p>About half the victims died from the virus....</p>
<p>The scientists intend to collect blood, urine and other samples from humans and to trap insects, rodents and other animals to test them for evidence of Lassa fever.</p>
<p>&quot;Handling [human] specimens might be a bit risky for those who are not immune,&quot; Dr. [Jordi] Casals [the Yale virologist who survived Lassa fever] said. None of the five other scientists are known to have immunity against the fever....  </p></td>
</tr>
