<p align="center"><strong><font size="+1">African Virus to be Studied in U.S.</font></strong> 

<br><br><center>By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN</center>
<p>Federal scientists at the Center for Disease Control in Atlanta expect to receive specimens today from victims of a new disease in Africa to help determine how serious a threat the infection might represent to the world. </p>
<p>In recent weeks, it has killed at least 335 people, including doctors and nurses who treated victims, in Zaire and the Sudan.&nbsp; The mode of spread is not known and no effective treatment exists. </p>
<p>Since the World Health Organization sent a team of doctors to investigate the outbreak in Zaire on Oct. 6, scientists at the Atlanta center and in Europe have identified the virus as one not previously known. </p>
<p>&quot;It is a new virus in the Marburg family,&quot; said Dr. William H. Foege, assistant to the director of the Center for Disease Control, in a telephone interview last night.... </p>
<p>Symptoms of the ailment are said to include high fever and bleeding.&nbsp; The virus is believed to affect the capillary blood vessels, which connect arteries and veins, and to interfere with the clotting mechanism, leading to lethal internal bleeding. </p>
<p>[T]wo Belgian doctors said that Belgian and other researchers had set a high priority on trying to develop something to help combat the infection.... </p>
<p>[S]erum from victims who had recovered from Marburg disease had proved ineffective in treating the new infection. </p></td>
